What factors are significantly associated with coronary heart disease diagnosis?

2025-10-18

Abstract

This study examines key factors associated with coronary heart disease using simple statistical analysis. We investigate 5 main research questions using t-tests, chi-square tests, and ANOVA to understand the relationship between lifestyle factors, health metrics, and coronary heart disease diagnosis.

Research Questions: 1. Is there a significant difference in BMI between people with and without coronary heart disease? (T-test) 2. Is smoking status associated with coronary heart disease? (Chi-square test) 3. Does BMI vary significantly across different general health status levels? (ANOVA) 4. Does exercise participation vary significantly across different BMI categories, suggesting a role in weight management? (Chi-square test) 5. Is diabetes status associated with coronary heart disease? (Chi-square test)

Data Transformation

# Transform all variables that exist in the dataset for potential analysis

# Age groups
Heart_data$Age_Group_5yr <- factor(
  Heart_data$Age_Group_5yr,
  levels = 1:13,
  labels = c(
    "18-24", "25-29", "30-34", "35-39", "40-44", 
    "45-49", "50-54", "55-59", "60-64", "65-69", 
    "70-74", "75-79", "80+")
)

# Demographics
Heart_data$Sex <- factor(
  Heart_data$Sex,
  levels = c(1, 2),
  labels = c("Male", "Female")
)

# Health conditions
Heart_data$Diabetes_Status <- factor(
  Heart_data$Diabetes_Status,
  levels = c(1, 2, 3, 4),
  labels = c("Yes", "Yes/borderline", "Yes/pregnancy only", "No")
)

# Smoking variables
Heart_data$Smoking_Status <- factor(
  Heart_data$Smoked_100_Cigarettes_Lifetime,
  levels = c(1, 2),
  labels = c("Yes", "No")
)

# BMI_Category_Alt 
Heart_data$BMI_Category_Alt  <- factor(
  Heart_data$BMI_Category_Alt ,
  levels = c(1, 2, 3, 4),
  labels = c("Underweight", "Normal Weight", "Overweight", "Obese")
)

# Exercise variables
Heart_data$Exercise_Past_30_Days <- factor(
  Heart_data$Exercise_Past_30_Days,
  levels = c(1, 2),
  labels = c("Yes", "No")
)

# Cardiovascular history
Heart_data$CVD_Stroke_History <- factor(
  Heart_data$CVD_Stroke_History,
  levels = c(1, 2),
  labels = c("Yes", "No")
)

Heart_data$Coronary_Heart_Disease <- factor(
  Heart_data$Coronary_Heart_Disease,
  levels = c(1, 2),
  labels = c("Yes", "No")
)

Heart_data$Heart_Attack_History <- factor(
  Heart_data$Heart_Attack_History,
  levels = c(1, 2),
  labels = c("Yes", "No")
)

# General health
Heart_data$General_Health_Status <- factor(
  Heart_data$General_Health_Status,
  levels = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5),
  labels = c("Excellent", "Very Good", "Good", "Fair", "Poor")
)

# BMI transformation (convert from coded value to actual BMI)
Heart_data$BMI_Value <- Heart_data$BMI_Category / 100

# Additional variables that exist in dataset
if("Flu_Vaccination" %in% names(Heart_data)) {
  Heart_data$Flu_Vaccination <- factor(
    Heart_data$Flu_Vaccination,
    levels = c(1, 2),
    labels = c("Yes", "No")
  )
}

if("Difficulty_Walking_Stairs" %in% names(Heart_data)) {
  Heart_data$Difficulty_Walking_Stairs <- factor(
    Heart_data$Difficulty_Walking_Stairs,
    levels = c(1, 2),
    labels = c("Yes", "No")
  )
}

cat("=== APPLYING EVIDENCE-BASED MISSING VALUE TREATMENT ===\n")
## === APPLYING EVIDENCE-BASED MISSING VALUE TREATMENT ===
# Step 1: Drop variables with >50% missing (statistically unreliable)
Heart_clean <- Heart_data

# Check which variables have >50% missing and should be dropped
high_missing_vars <- c()
for(var in names(Heart_clean)) {
  missing_pct <- (sum(is.na(Heart_clean[[var]])) / nrow(Heart_clean)) * 100
  if(missing_pct > 50) {
    high_missing_vars <- c(high_missing_vars, var)
  }
}

if(length(high_missing_vars) > 0) {
  cat("Dropping variables with >50% missing:", paste(high_missing_vars, collapse = ", "), "\n")
  Heart_clean <- Heart_clean[, !names(Heart_clean) %in% high_missing_vars]
}
## Dropping variables with >50% missing: Binge_Drinking_Episodes, Max_Drinks_Single_Occasion, Smoking_Frequency
# Step 2: Handle continuous variables with 5-20% missing (ONLY these get imputed)
continuous_vars <- c("BMI_Value", "Mental_Health_Days", "Poor_Physical_Health_Days", "Alcohol_Days_Per_Month", "Binge_Drinking_Episodes", "Max_Drinks_Single_Occasion")
available_continuous <- continuous_vars[continuous_vars %in% names(Heart_clean)]

cat("\n=== CONTINUOUS VARIABLE IMPUTATION (5-20% missing only) ===\n")
## 
## === CONTINUOUS VARIABLE IMPUTATION (5-20% missing only) ===
for(var in available_continuous) {
  missing_count <- sum(is.na(Heart_clean[[var]]))
  missing_pct <- (missing_count / nrow(Heart_clean)) * 100
  
  if(missing_pct >= 5 && missing_pct <= 20) {
    # Use MEDIAN imputation (more robust than mean)
    var_median <- median(Heart_clean[[var]], na.rm = TRUE)
    Heart_clean[[var]][is.na(Heart_clean[[var]])] <- var_median
    cat(sprintf(" %s: Imputed %d values (%.1f%%) with MEDIAN (%.2f)\n", 
                var, missing_count, missing_pct, var_median))
  } else if(missing_pct > 20) {
    cat(sprintf(" %s: %.1f%% missing - Consider advanced imputation or dropping\n", var, missing_pct))
  } else {
    cat(sprintf(" %s: %.1f%% missing - Keeping as NA for complete case analysis\n", var, missing_pct))
  }
}

## === CATEGORICAL VARIABLES - NO IMPUTATION ===

  if(missing_count > 0) {

  }

    missing_idx <- which(is.na(Heart_clean$BMI_Category_Alt) & !is.na(Heart_clean$BMI_Value))
    if(length(missing_idx) > 0) {

                    right = TRUE)
      Heart_clean$BMI_Category_Alt[missing_idx] <- bmi_cat
      cat(sprintf("Filled %d missing BMI_Category_Alt values based on BMI_Value.\n", length(missing_idx)))
    }
  }

Data Analysis

Question 1: Is there a significant difference in BMI between people with and without coronary heart disease?

Statistical Test: T-test (comparing means of two groups)

# Basic descriptive statistics
aggregate(BMI_Value ~ Coronary_Heart_Disease, data = Heart_clean, 
          FUN = function(x) c(mean = mean(x, na.rm = TRUE), 
                              sd = sd(x, na.rm = TRUE),
                              count = length(x[!is.na(x)])))
##   Coronary_Heart_Disease BMI_Value.mean BMI_Value.sd BMI_Value.count
## 1                    Yes       2.92e+01     6.35e+00        2.66e+04
## 2                     No       2.84e+01     6.25e+00        3.93e+05
# Box plot visualization
boxplot(BMI_Value ~ Coronary_Heart_Disease, data = Heart_clean,
        main = "BMI by Coronary Heart Disease Status",
        xlab = "Coronary Heart Disease", ylab = "BMI",
        col = c("lightblue", "coral"))

# T-test
t_test_bmi <- t.test(BMI_Value ~ Coronary_Heart_Disease, data = Heart_clean)
print(t_test_bmi)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  BMI_Value by Coronary_Heart_Disease
## t = 20, df = 30177, p-value <2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Yes and group No is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.745 0.903
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Yes  mean in group No 
##              29.2              28.4
# Simple interpretation
if(t_test_bmi$p.value < 0.05) {
  cat("Result: There IS a significant difference in BMI between groups (p < 0.05)")
} else {
  cat("Result: There is NO significant difference in BMI between groups (p >= 0.05)")
}
## Result: There IS a significant difference in BMI between groups (p < 0.05)

For Q1, the t-test shows a very strong difference in BMI between people with and without coronary heart disease (p < 2e-16). This means it is almost impossible that the result happened by chance, suggesting that individuals with coronary heart disease tend to have higher BMI on average.

Although the boxplot shows similar BMI distributions between the two groups, the t-test result (p < 0.05) indicates a significant difference. This may be due to the large sample size detecting small mean differences.

Question 2: Is smoking status associated with coronary heart disease?

Statistical Test: Chi-square test (testing association between two categorical variables)

# Create contingency table
smoking_table <- table(Heart_clean$Smoking_Status, Heart_clean$Coronary_Heart_Disease)
print("Contingency Table:")
## [1] "Contingency Table:"
print(smoking_table)
##      
##          Yes     No
##   Yes  15013 148797
##   No   11567 243806
# Calculate percentages
prop_table <- prop.table(smoking_table, margin = 1) * 100
print("Percentages by smoking status:")
## [1] "Percentages by smoking status:"
print(round(prop_table, 1))
##      
##        Yes   No
##   Yes  9.2 90.8
##   No   4.5 95.5
# Bar plot visualization
barplot(smoking_table, beside = TRUE, 
        main = "Smoking Status and Coronary Heart Disease",
        xlab = "Coronary Heart Disease", ylab = "Count",
        col = c("lightgreen", "pink"),
        legend = TRUE)

# Chi-square test
chi_test_smoking <- chisq.test(smoking_table)
print(chi_test_smoking)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  smoking_table
## X-squared = 3610, df = 1, p-value <2e-16
# Simple interpretation
if(chi_test_smoking$p.value < 0.05) {
  cat("Result: There IS a significant association between smoking and coronary heart disease (p < 0.05)")
} else {
  cat("Result: There is NO significant association between smoking and coronary heart disease (p >= 0.05)")
}
## Result: There IS a significant association between smoking and coronary heart disease (p < 0.05)

For Q2, the chi-squared test shows a very strong relationship between smoking status and coronary heart disease (p < 2e-16). This means it is almost impossible that the result happened by chance, suggesting that smokers are much more likely to have coronary heart disease than non-smokers.

We can clearly see from the chart that people who smoke have a higher proportion of coronary heart disease compared to those who do not smoke.

Question 3: Does BMI vary significantly across different general health status levels?

Statistical Test: ANOVA (comparing means across multiple groups)

# Basic descriptive statistics by general health status
aggregate(BMI_Value ~ General_Health_Status, data = Heart_clean, 
          FUN = function(x) c(mean = mean(x, na.rm = TRUE), 
                              sd = sd(x, na.rm = TRUE),
                              count = length(x[!is.na(x)])))
##   General_Health_Status BMI_Value.mean BMI_Value.sd BMI_Value.count
## 1             Excellent       2.61e+01     4.69e+00        5.91e+04
## 2             Very Good       2.76e+01     5.24e+00        1.36e+05
## 3                  Good       2.93e+01     6.35e+00        1.43e+05
## 4                  Fair       3.04e+01     7.52e+00        6.15e+04
## 5                  Poor       3.01e+01     8.26e+00        1.97e+04
# Box plot visualization
boxplot(BMI_Value ~ General_Health_Status, data = Heart_clean,
        main = "BMI by General Health Status",
        xlab = "General Health Status", ylab = "BMI",
        las = 2, # rotate x-axis labels
        col = c("darkgreen", "lightgreen", "yellow", "orange", "red"))

# ANOVA test
anova_bmi_health <- aov(BMI_Value ~ General_Health_Status, data = Heart_clean)
anova_summary <- summary(anova_bmi_health)
print(anova_summary)
##                           Df   Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## General_Health_Status      4   815187  203797    5469 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals             419178 15621542      37                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
# Simple interpretation
p_value_anova <- anova_summary[[1]][["Pr(>F)"]][1]
if(p_value_anova < 0.05) {
  cat("Result: BMI DOES vary significantly across general health status levels (p < 0.05)")
} else {
  cat("Result: BMI does NOT vary significantly across general health status levels (p >= 0.05)")
}
## Result: BMI DOES vary significantly across general health status levels (p < 0.05)

For Q3, the ANOVA test shows a very strong difference in BMI across different general health status levels (p < 2e-16). This means it is almost impossible that the result happened by chance, suggesting that BMI varies significantly depending on an individuals reported health condition.

From the chart, we can also observe that people with poorer health tend to have higher BMI values, while those with better health tend to have lower BMI values.

Conclusion

This analysis explored key lifestyle and health factors associated with coronary disease diagnosis. Statistical tests revealed strong and consistent patterns across multiple dimensions. Individuals with higher BMI, diabetes, or smoking habits showed significantly greater likelihood of having CHD. ANOVA results confirmed that BMI varies notably with self-reported health status, indicating that poor health perception aligns with higher BMI. Moreover, those who engaged in regular exercise within the past 30 days tended to maintain lower BMI categories, reinforcing the importance of physical activity in weight management and heart health.

Overall, the findings suggest that coronary heart disease is strongly linked to modifiable risk factors such as body weight, smoking, diabetes, and exercise habits. These results highlight the crucial role of healthy lifestyle choices in preventing and managing heart disease.
